    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2895682089" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2895682089" />
    <a title="Jemppu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85472654-jemppu"><img alt="Jemppu" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609706553p2/85472654.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2895682089?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jemppu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jemppu" href="/user/show/85472654-jemppu">Jemppu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2895682089" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer429035644890864507">The book&apos;s most formidable strength comes from the ability of it&apos;s prose to paint powerfully visceral images. Full of vivid spanning shots of beautifully gritty cityscape, and couple passages of surprisingly enthralling surrealistic pictures. <br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[These paintings are also persistently turned to depictions of viscous, mucous creatures, fleshy gore, and dissections of tools used to inflict said gore - feature which too is brought to life effectively, but which for me personally lost most</span></span>
  <span id="freeText429035644890864507" style="display:none">The book's most formidable strength comes from the ability of it's prose to paint powerfully visceral images. Full of vivid spanning shots of beautifully gritty cityscape, and couple passages of surprisingly enthralling surrealistic pictures. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[These paintings are also persistently turned to depictions of viscous, mucous creatures, fleshy gore, and dissections of tools used to inflict said gore - feature which too is brought to life effectively, but which for me personally lost most of it's initial fascination for prolonged stretches by mere oversaturation. Until towards the end, when there began to emerge something greatly alleviating from the comedic value of the continued insistence of the general ooziness of <b>all</b> things - from soil to weather to eating -, leaving me at times puzzled as to if such a borderline satiric approach was indeed intentional. The very ending too however, I saw, forgave a lot.<br /><br />Regardless, I'm afraid my lasting impression of the whole experience will be colored as: relentlessly gooey.<br /><br />I was most intrigued by the imagination stimulating concepts of 'choice-theft', and 'mental nourishment' - feeding on dreams, which I would've welcomed even more extensive exploration on: examples on consequences to psyches of individuals subjected to such a dreadful threat. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Miéville's telling is evocative, and world building strong, with finely nuanced yet noteworthy linguistic choices to help support the perception of it, which I found myself appreciative for. I shall thus be interested to see how these show in their other work - hopefully on an arena less pus drenched.</span>
  <a data-text-id="429035644890864507" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

